(62, 4, 0, 'GRDJEV01I040079', 60, NULL, 'Radial Basis Function Neural Network based classifier for Diagnosing of MCI /AD using Multimodal Neuroimaging', 'Image processing', 2, 7, '', 'Medical images', 'Neuroimaging has played a very important role in the diagnosis of brain degeneration disorders, such as Alzheimer’s disease (AD) and Mild Cognitive Impairment (MCI). To identify different stages of Alzheimer’s disease and efficient analysis system has been developed for magnetic resonance Imaging (MRI) and positron emission tomography (PET) Neuroimages using machine learning methods. The classifiers we use are Decision Tree (DT), and Radial Basis Function Neural Network (RBFNN) is used to identify a Normal, MCI and AD patients. We assessed the performance comparison of these classification methods in terms of different performance measures such as accuracy, sensitivity and specificity', '', 'R.RAMYA', 'SRI VENKATESWARA COLLEGE OF ENGINEERING', 'ramyaravi678@gmail.com', '9597713419', 'sri venkateswara college of engineering', 'sriperambudur.', 'kanchipuram', '604001', 'tamil nadu', 'India', 'GRDJE/V01/I04/0079/1459534256_paper-work-finalff.docx', '{"Title construction of manuscript was good":"Agree","Introduction covers each part of work done area Introduction covers all required thorough":"Agree","Knowledge to understand the topic":"Agree","Material method was given with company detail":"Partial Agree","All materials were covered which was used in that work":"Disagree","Method was describe in details":"Partial Agree","Method was describe with quantity of materials used in that work":"Partial Agree","Result was discussed thoroughly to understand the effect of work":"Agree","Result was discussed with mathematical model Application":"Agree","Acknowledgement was described all help which was received during the work":"Disagree","I do not have any objection if this work was published in this journal":"Partial Agree","comment":"Dear Professor,\\r\\n\\tDuring the time of plagiarism checking of this paper titled as \\"Performance Comparison between Decision Tree and Radial Basis Function Neural Network on Diagnosing of MCI /AD using Multimodal Neuroimaging\\" only 71% Unique content and 29% plagiarized content. \\r\\n\\tAs per my point of view the proposed work does not show the significant novelty and improvement.\\r\\n\\tTherefore the review Comments is Minor Revision.\\r\\nThank You.\\r\\n"}', 0, '', '', 0, 0, '', NULL, 5, 'GRDJE/V01/I04/0079/', '3', 0, 0, 0, '2016-03-20 22:45:43', 0, '2016-04-01 23:44:09', 1, 0),
(63, 4, 0, 'GRDJEV01I040080', 33, NULL, 'Multi-Agent Mobile Robot Navigation through Genetic-Fuzzy Algorithm', 'Robotic Navigation', 2, 6, '', 'Mobile Robot Navigation; Multi-agent System; Coordination; Potential Field Method; Fuzzy Logic Control; Genetic Algorithm', 'The present paper deals with the navigation of multiple wheeled robots working in a common dynamic environment in a decentralized manner. Two different motion planning approaches have been proposed to solve the said problem. In Approach 1, automatic design of a Mamdani-type Fuzzy Logic Controller (FLC) using a binary-coded Genetic Algorithm (GA) has been considered. On the other hand, a potential field- based motion planner has been developed in the next approach. Since, the robots are agents and all the time competition is not good, a strategic approach has been proposed to solve the conflicts related to coordination among agents. Performance of the developed approaches have been tested through computer simulations. Computational complexity of both the approaches are also compared to see the feasibility of their on-line implementations. It has been observed that proposed coordination strategy along with the developed motion planners are found to generate movement of the robots in a human-like manner.', '[1]	Alami, R., Chatila, R., Fleury, S. and Ingrand, F. (1998). An architecture for autonomy, International Journal of Robotics Research. 17(4), 315–337.\r\n[2]	Asada, M., Kitano, H., Noda, I. and Veloso, M. (1999). Robocup: today and tomorrow– what we have and learned, Artificial Intelligence. 110, 193–214.\r\n[3]	Bemporad, A., Luca, A. D. and Orilo, G. (1996). Local incremental planning for a car-like robot navigating among obstacles, Proc. of IEEE Conference on Robotics and Automation, Minneapolis, Minnesoia, pp. 1205–1211.\r\n[4]	Bennewitz, M. and Burgard, W. (2000). A probabilistic method for planning collision-free trajectories of multiple mobile robots, Proc. of the Workshop Service Robotics Appl