(255, 5, 0, 'GRDJEV01I050025', 0, NULL, 'Resume Ranking Using NLP & ML', 'Artificial Intelligence, Machine Learning, Morphological Analysis, Natural Language Process', 5, 12, '', 'Natural Language Processing, Machine Learning, ElasticSearch, Ranking, Scrapy, Scikit learn, PostgreSQL', 'Using Natural Language Processing(NLP) and (ML)Machine Learning to rank the resumes according to the given constraint, this intelligent system ranks the resume of any format according to the given constraints or the following requirements provided by the client company. We will basically take the bulk of input resume from the client company and that client company will also provided the requirement and the constraints according to which the resume shall be ranked by our system. Moreover the details acquired from the resumes, our system shall be reading the candidates social profiles (like LinkedIn, Github etc) which will the more genuine information about that candidate.', '', 'Sayed ZainulAbideen Mohd Sadiq', 'AIKTC-School of Engineering & Technolgy', 'zainul.sayed28@gmail.com', '8451055885', 'G/03, Jijamata Nagar', 'Dr. E Mosis Road', 'Worli', '400018', 'Maharashtra', 'India', 'GRDJE/V01/I05/0025/1459794382_ResumeRankingIEEE.doc', '', 0, '', '', 0, 0, '', NULL, 1, 'GRDJE/V01/I05/0025/', '3', 0, 0, 0, '2016-04-04 23:56:23', 0, '2016-04-04 23:56:23', 0, 0),
(256, 5, 0, 'GRDJEV01I050026', 0, NULL, 'EXPERIMENTAL STUDY ON THE STABILIZATION OF SOIL BY USING GLASS BOTTLES', 'soil stabilaization', 5, 10, '', 'Atterberg limits, Subgrade material, Stabilization, Compaction, California bearing ratio, Glass Powder.', 'This paper assesses the stabilizing effect of powdered glass on  soil. Broken waste glass was collected and ground into powder form suitable for addition to the soil in varying proportions namely 4%, 8%, 12%, 16% and 20%  by weight of the soil sample throughout. Consequently, the moisture content, specific gravity, particle size distribution and Atterberg limits tests were carried out to classify the soil using the ASSHTO classification system. Based on the results, the soil sample obtained corresponded to Group A-6 soils identified as ‘fair to poor’ soil type in terms of use as drainage and subgrade material. This justified stabilization of the soil. Thereafter, compaction, California bearing ratio (CBR)  were carried out on the soil with and without the addition of the powdered glass. The results showed improvement in the maximum dry density values on addition of the powdered glass and with corresponding gradual increase up to 16% glass powder content after which it started to decrease at 20% powdered glass content. The maximum dry density and optimum moisture content were obtained at 16% of glass content. The highest CBR values of 10.1 were obtained at 16% glass powder content and 5mm penetration for  unsoaked  treated samples . With further addition of glass content by 20% decreased the values. Therefore, the optimum value of OMC,MDD and UCS,CBR was obtained for 16% of glass content.', '', 'B.SURESH', 'K.S.R. COLLEGE OF ENGINEERING', 'sindhiyacivil@gmail.com', '8122530225', '8/1758, PONNAMMAL NAGAR', 'POOLUVAPATI(P.O), PANDIAN NAGAR(EAST)', 'TIRUPUR', '641602', 'TAMILNADU', 'India', 'GRDJE/V01/I05/0026/1459832309_ssss.docx', '', 0, '', '', 0, 0, '', NULL, 1, 'GRDJE/V01/I05/0026/', '3', 0, 0, 0, '2016-04-05 10:28:29', 0, '2016-04-05 10:28:29', 0, 0),
(257, 5, 0, 'GRDJEV01I050027', 0, NULL, 'Purifying Test Cases for ImprovingFault Localization', 'Software Testing', 1, 4, '', 'Test case purification, test case atomization, test case slicing, rank refinement, assertion', 'Software fault localization is one of the most expensive, tedious and time consuming activities in program debugging. Therefore, there is a high demand for automatic fault localization that can guide programmers to the locations of faults, with minimal human intervention. This demand has led to proposal and development of various method, each of which seeks to make the fault localization process more effective in its own unique and creative way. In this paper we use concept of test case purification for improving fault localization. The goal of test case purification is to separate existing test cases into small fractions called purified test cases, which consists of three major phases: test case atomization, test case slicing, and rank refinement, purified test cases consist of only one assertion statement in each test case.', '', 'Akthar Nazir', 'SRM UNIVERSITY', 'aktharnazir532@gmail.com', '7895654013', 'Akash Vihar Colony', 'near SRM University', 'modinagar, ghaziabad, uttar pradesh', '201204', 'uttar pradesh', 'India', 'GRDJE/V01/I05/0027/1459837249_akthar-paper-publish.docx', '', 0, '', '', 0, 0, '', NULL, 1, 'GRDJE/V01/I05/0027/', '1', 0, 0, 0, '2016-04-05 11:50:51', 0, '2016-04-05 11:50:51', 0, 0),
(258, 5, 0, 'GRDJEV01I050028', 0, NULL, 'Log analytics using ELK stack on Cloud platform', 'Data mining and cloud ', 2, 12, '', 'Amazon web server, Lucene, Elastic search, Logstash, Kibana', '	”Log analytics using ELK stack” is an implementation of Logstash for extracting and indexing, Elasticsearch for searching and kibana for visualizing which are combined together to perform operation on logs. Elasticsearch is a Lucene based search server. Elasticsearch provides a distributed, multitenant-capable full-text search engine. Logstash tool to collect, index, and forward events and log messages. Kibana is used to represent the data in a graphical and statistical way.\r\n       In this system we use the logs from Elastic Load Balancer, a service of Amazon Web Servers with the help of Logstash. Then these logs are indexed via logstash and represented through Kibana.These logs are properly formatted and ready for information retrieval. Thus,a system admin can check the behaviour of the whole server or a particular component by going through the logs and analyzing the system status. This will help in identifying the fallback of the server and the system administrator can take necessary actions to resolve the problems if any.\r\n', '', 'Palak Loya', 'MIT Pune', 'elkprojectbe@gmail.com', '9595904575', 'MIT', 'Kothrud ', 'Pune', '411038', 'Maharashtra', 'India', 'GRDJE/V01/I05/0028/1459839460_Projectpaper.docx', '', 0, '', '', 0, 0, '', NULL, 1, 'GRDJE/V01/I05/0028/', '1', 0, 0, 0, '2016-04-05 12:27:41', 0, '2016-04-05 12:27:41', 0, 0),
(259, 5, 0, 'GRDJEV01I050029', 0, NULL, 'Handwritten Devnagri Character Recognition', 'Image Processing', 1, 7, '', 'Devnagri Characters, Multilayer perceptron, K-Nearest Neighbour, Naive Bayes ', 'Recognition of handwritten characters has been a popular research area for many years. Devnagari script is a major script of India and is widely used for various languages. In this paper we propose a system to recognize devnagri handwritten characters. Total 60 devnagri characters (50 letters and 10 digits) are taken in to consideration. 60 samples of each character i.e. total 3600 samples are used for features extraction. Classification is done by four different classifiers which are Multilayer perceptron, K-Nearest Neighbour, Naive Bayes classifier and Classification tree. Performance of different classifiers is compared.98.9 % accuracy is obtained by Multilayer perceptron.     ', '', 'Prof. Shraddha V.Shelke', 'K. K. Wagh Institute of engineering Education and Research Nashik, Maharashtra', 'svshelke@kkwagh.edu.in', '7350281736', 'Flat No : 3, Shree Tirumala ShreeNivasa Appt. Nilmani Colony', 'Near Samrat Sweets, Rajiv Nagar', 'Nashik', '422009', 'Maharashtra', 'India', 'GRDJE/V01/I05/0029/1459841649_GRDpaper..docx', '', 0, '', '', 0, 0, '', NULL, 1, 'GRDJE/V01/I05/0029/', '1', 0, 0, 0, '2016-04-05 13:04:10', 0, '2016-04-05 13:04:10', 0, 0);
